shtead, Surrey, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1251–AFT 1287":"circa 1251–na 1287","1250–1287":"1250–1287","1288–1355":"1288–1355","1251–1287":"1251–1287","AFT 1287":"na 1287","1259":"1259","1355":"1355","1288":"1288","1287":"1287","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","about 1251":"circa 1251","Ashtead, Surrey, England":"Ashtead, Surrey, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"about 1251–AFT 1287":"about 1251–after 1287","1250–1287":"1250–1287","1288–1355":"1288–1355","1251–1287":"1251–1287","AFT 1287":"after 1287","1259":"1259","1355":"1355","1288":"1288","1287":"1287","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","about 1251":"about 1251","Ashtead, Surrey, England":"Ashtead, Surrey, England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>parker</i> ‘park-keeper’ (Old French <i>parquier</i>, <i>parchier</i>), an officer employed to look after deer and other game in a hunting park (see   Park   1). This surname is also very common among African Americans. It has also been recorded since medieval times in Ireland.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish names."],"variants":[{"name":"Parkman","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>park</i> ‘enclosure, game preserve, park’ (Old French <i>parc</i>) + <i>man</i>, sometimes for one living at or near such a place but probably more often denoting someone employed to look after after deer and other game in a hunting park; compare   Parker  .","occupational name denoting the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of someone called <i>Park</i> (see   Park   2)."]},{"name":"Parkerson","meanings":["English: from the occupational name   Parker   + patronymic <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Parkey","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): dialect pronunciation of   Parker  . <i>Parker</i> has a long history in Macclesfield, Manchester, and Bridgnorth."]},{"name":"Park","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Sang, Sung, Yong, Jung, Jong, Chan, Jae, Jin, Kwang, Kyung, Myung, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Louise","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Louis  , introduced to England in the 17th century. Like   Louisa  , it has remained perennially popular and is currently frequently used as a component of compound names such as <i>Ella-Louise</i>, <i>Sophie-Louise</i>, and <i>Tia-Louise</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Louise Parker was born about 1251, in Ashtead, Surrey, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Ralph de Aston. She died after 1287."},"et":{"about 1251–AFT 1287":"umbes 1251–pärast 1287","1250–1287":"1250–1287","1288–1355":"1288–1355","1251–1287":"1251–1287","AFT 1287":"pärast 1287","1259":"12